        public static <T> TypeBehavior.ValueFactory<T> valueFactoryFromInstances​(T... values)

      • singletonValueFactory

        public static <T> TypeBehavior.ValueFactory<T> singletonValueFactory​(T value)
        Creates a simple TypeBehavior.ValueFactory that returns the sameinstance each time it is called. After all instances are used, it starts over at the first. This is for use with checkEqualsAndHashCode(List), and you should use it instead of a lambda like () -> value whenever the type enforces singleton usage, because otherwise checkEqualsAndHashCode(List) will expect the return values to be equal only value and not by reference.
        Type Parameters:
        T - the value type
        Parameters:
        value - the instance
        Returns:
        a value factory

      • checkEqualsAndHashCode

        public static <T> void checkEqualsAndHashCode​(java.util.List<TypeBehavior.ValueFactory<T>> valueFactories)
        Implements a standard test suite for custom implementations of equals() and hashCode().

        The valueFactories parameter is a list of value factories. Each factory must produce only instances that are equal to each other, and not equal to the instances produced by any of the other factories. The test suite verifies the following:

        • For any instance a created by any of the factories, a.equals(a) is true, a.equals(null) is false, and a.equals(x) where x is an instance of a different class is false.
        • For any two instances a and b created by the same factory, a.equals(b), b.equals(a), and a.hashCode() == b.hashCode() are all true.
        • For any two instances a and b created by different factories, a.equals(b) and b.equals(a) are false (there is no requirement that the hash codes are different).

        If the type uses a singleton/interning pattern so that there can only be one instance with a particular value, use singletonValueFactory(Object) to indicate that that is deliberate; otherwise checkEqualsAndHashCode(List) will assume that it is a test logic error if it sees the same instance twice.

        Type Parameters:
        T - the value type
        Parameters:
        valueFactories - list of factories for distinct values
        Throws:
        java.lang.AssertionError - if a test condition fails
